<user_id>114523318047574794098</user_id>< user_name>
Rod Rod<//user_name>
<Time>1562797707355</Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
This place is a heavens sent for handymen and DIYers. I find it to have the best prices for many things that would have cost me more than triple at Home Depot or Lowes. If you are a truly experienced maintenance/diy person chances are you'd be able to identify items that are casually ignored by the common shopper but  could actually  be considered a treasure find. Don't be discouraged if some items are cosmetically old loooking or rusted because they are easily cleaned. Visit regularly because you wouldn't know what newly acquired items they may have at some particular week or month. I have been a long time shopper at this place and I have save a lot of money.<//review>

< review>
It's a shame I have to write this review for the Dublin branch since I'm a regular at Fremont and their staff is fantastic. I ordered my food well in advance of my arrival time. Once I got to the restaurant, my pickup was not only not ready but they had me waiting for an hour. After about half an hour of patiently waiting, I approached the cashier with a status request and he was absolutely rude and said people have been waiting longer than me. I gave him the benefit of doubt and walked away. However, after the next half hour when I asked again they said they needed to check and I should wait more. I cancelled my order and walked out and they didn't even bat an eye. Two horrible kids who have been tasked with handling customer service and they have no idea what they're doing. To identify them one is a white kid and the other is a brown kid with round glasses and long hair. Stay away from this branch and, if you get one of these two as your servers, God help you! Never going there again

Update: after I posted my initial review, this was the Owner‚Äôs response:
‚ÄúOnce again I urge you to remove the offensive comments about describing our staff. This young man feels threatened by your behavior and we will not tolerate this. We reserve the right to serve whom we feel safe with. This includes our Fremont location.‚Äù

This is shameful! Instead of apologizing to me for terrible customer service you are defending the person who treated me so rudely! Furthermore, I stated in my review that I waited, very patiently, for almost an hour. At no point was I rowdy or impatient. That‚Äôs what grieves me that I was the one treated so poorly and you paint yourself as the victim. You should be ashamed of yourself for even writing a response like this.</review>

T Mon<//name>
< Review>
I've dined here a few times, so my feedback is based on mutiple visits, menu items and staffing. The food choices are interesting, mostly American dishes with a Pakistani / Indian twist (wich means, added spices and flavorings). One of my favorites is the fried chicken, and the Americano burger. Other sandwiches and dishes are good too, but you have to be in the mood for the flavors. For others it's a little taste of fast food back home. Staff has always been pleasant, prices are about right, not over priced. Seating area is on the smaller side, so try to reserve or show up off peak hours, otherwise  you'll have to wait. Parking is good. They are expanding outdoor seating, which should be helpful in the summer.< /Review>
<pictures>None</pictures></record>
</dataset><record>

< Review>
With good coffee being commonplace now, does it really matter which one I stop at?  YES!    This place was a coffee roaster first, selling specially blended coffee to restaurants, and their coffee is great!  They then opened the cafe and made it a super casual, comfortable place.  Don't let that fool you, though, the staff are relaxed but they are really working for you, just making it look easy.  It must be a good place to work!  And the roaster now gets to do single origins and new blends, whatever the beans seem to want, this has got to be more fun than blending for the same restaurants every week.< /Review>

< text>
If you're in SLO and looking for amazing coffee or espresso drinks, and treats that will blow your mind, then be sure to visit Coastal Peaks Roasters. My drink of choice is a breve cappuccino, but the other morning they happened to have bacon and date scones, and holy cow... what a combination!

We also love to pick up a pound of beans for domestic duty when we're there, and these will also delight your senses. Even their decaf beans are fantastic, with none of that tinny aftertaste you'll get from other brands.

The newly redesigned interior makes you want to settle in for the day with a good book or a friend for some good conversation.< /text>

<name>Leila Rahil<//name>< Rate>
4< /Rate>
<Review>Though kind of hidden in the strip mall it is located in as it is kind of an industrial park area, this place is a hidden gem!

Loved everything about my experience here! It is a functioning coffee roaster as well as a lil cafe, so you can smell the awesome coffee from the street!

I had the thai chicken wrap w/the pasta salad and cookie meal and the Matcha latte and for $11.63 w/tax and tip, it was worth every penny! The thai vinaigrette that comes on the wrap is Nom-some! And the Matcha Latte was perfection! The pasta salad (and they give you a healthy portion, so I took half of mine on the road w/me for a snack later) was very tasty and the cranberry oatmeal cookie I had, though small, was also delish!

The indoor decor is cute and captures their coffee expertise with ample seating. The staff was nice and my order came out fairly fast.

They have a great selection of loose leaf teas as well.

I would definitely go out of my way to make a return visit the next time I am in SLO.< /Review>< date>
1407192376210< /date>

<Text>Im 28 and have never been to the dentist. Mostly out of an irrational fear I had as a child that I never really got over as an adult.... But I started h aving pain in my tooth. A friend of mine who also has a fear of the dentist recommended Dr. Park. And I figured i have to go... Might as well give them a shot.

I am so glad I did! All the staff there were friendly and helpful and answered all my questions (and I am one to ask a-lot of questions.) And Unfortunately I have to have a root canal.... But Dr. Park and her assistant Kesia were just so amazing! They explained everything to me ahead of time and anytime they did anything they let me know so I was ready for it.

They made sure that I didnt feel anything before starting the procedure and let me know with my hands if i felt any pain so they could stop. I opted for the nitrous option to help me relax. < text>
EMMANUEL OLASEHINWA (MBA, CBAP, PMI-ACP)

Fail fast and discover success early! This is my story with PMI-ACP certification. I am a certified Business Analyst working with a Tech company in Ottawa, CA supporting Agile change transition.

After failing in my 1st attempt , l discovered Cornelius Fichtner's ACP podcast and simulation materials. The explanations on Agile domain were real and practical for me to understand.  At first, the simulations questions appeared too tough for me however, given that the simulation tool is design to explains why each answer options is right or wrong really help my understanding and confidence building to re-take the exam. I combined this materials with Mike Griffith's PMI-ACP exam prep, navigate the ACP blogs to be aware of other students experiences and all of this strategies help me build confidence. l became PMI-ACP certified mid 2019.

I therefore recommend these resources as a sure path for PMI-ACP success. Thanks to OSP International.</text>

< review>
I registered for the PMP prepcast premium package in 2020, but because it was closer to the end of the year I was mentally prepared to take the exam under the new ECO. I found prepcast very honest about the value and training that they offered with this transition. I ended up taking their booster course as well. Here‚Äôs what I liked about prepcast:
1)	The self-paced training highlights key information from the PMBok and gives you additional resources not covered in the guides that are relevant
2)	The exam simulator is very good at disciplining your mind for a 4 hour exam and training you to focus on reading ambiguous questions and choosing from a set of answers that all look very good.
3)	The live feedback on the exam simulator was very useful in providing me with clarifications from experts when I needed them, and very promptly.
4)	The detailed answers on the exam reviews were also really good at helping me learn from the right as well as the wrong answers. I learned a lot from these and how to look for hints to answer the questions.

Here‚Äôs what I think needs improvement:
1)	The prepcast exam simulator questions do not resemble the exam. The actual exam is far more ambiguous. I realize the 2021 ECO was just rolled out, but I would recommend tuning the exam questions accordingly. Having said this, using a strong exam simulator is key in learning how to respond to questions even if the questions don‚Äôt resemble the actual exam. The simulator is still very good at training you to decipher questions.< /review>

< Review>
I planned to give my exam on 31 December 2020 because the syllabus and the exam pattern were about to change after that day. I finished my practice Rita Mulchay's PMP Exam Prep Ninth Edition by the end of the third week of December 2020. I contacted my instructor, Mr Junaid, from the PMI Lahore chapter, and I asked him what I could do to increase my success chances in the PMP Exam. He recommended that if I am willing to spend a little bit of money, the Prepcast simulator for PMP is the way to go. The advantages of this simulator are given below:
1. You can use the simulator in a wide variety of ways. You can have small, focused quizzes (based on knowledge groups, process groups, not answered before, etc.) or have a complete full-fledged exam simulation. Using this, you can target the specific areas where your concepts are weak.
2. Another nice thing about the simulator is that in each question, you can understand four new concepts in a sense. The correct answer is given with its explanation, and the three wrong choices are explained too. The explanation of why wrong and why correct leads you to understand four different PMI concepts comprehensively with each question.
3. The scenario-based questions are either of the same difficulty or a higher difficulty level than the actual exam. This makes you exam ready.
After just using this simulator for just a little more than a week, I succeeded in the PMP Exam, securing the above target in all process groups.<//Review>

<Text>I can't recommend this product highly enough.  I passed my PMP exam over the weekend (first try) and this tool was basically the only one I used for the last 3-4 weeks of my exam prep.

Things I found most useful about the product:

-You can do as few or as many questions as you like - if you only have 20 minutes before dinner, you can do 10 questions!  If you want it to be longer, you can do up to 100.

-You can tailor your practice exams to the areas where you're weaker (and this is easy to do since each practice exam shows your results breakdown in detail).

-The answers are reviewed in great detail - not only the correct answer but why the others are incorrect.  This is really important for the PMP!!!  Trying to memorize everything won't work, you have to really internalize the concepts.  Practicing the exam questions is the ONLY way to properly prepare for this kind of exam, in my opinion.

-Five full-length exams is the PERFECT amount for practicing.  For me, this worked very well - I did one apiece on Saturday and Sunday in the weekends leading up to my test.  On the weekdays in between, I did shorter practice tests focusing on my weaker areas.  I saved the last full length one for the weekend before my test.

I also have to applaud the responsiveness of their support staff.  At one point I had a question about one of the exams and I got a response within an hour, tops.  I went back and forth with the person several times to clarify something and she was extremely polite, quick, and direct with her responses.

Lastly - I love that they offer free exams to give the flavor of how it works.  If you're on the fence about purchasing the membership, go ahead and do the free trial so you can get an idea of what it offers (and then purchase it - you won't regret it).  I could not have passed my exam without this amazing practice tool, it was worth every penny.<//Text><Gmap_id>0x80dcdaea30496c3b:0x6197bf09e1400df8<//Gmap_id>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

< text>
I used the PMP Exam Simulator 2021 as a study and practice guide to pass the Project Management Institute's Project Management Professional (PMP) certification exam, in conjunction with the PMBOK guide.  In 21 hours of online study, quizzes and practice exams I answered 56% of the simulator's available 2,150 questions.  I did about 50 separate quizzes of 10 to 60 questions each and 3 full blown (180 questions and about 3 hours each) practice exams, of which I passed two and failed one.  This studying and practice translated into an "above target" grade on the actual PMI on-line PMP certification exam.  That exam also consisted of 180 questions, that I took 3 of the available 4 hours to complete. I credit the PMP Exam Simulator 2021 with providing good studying information and practice structure that directly led to my good exam performance.< /text>

1599500337572</Date>
<rating>5<//rating><review>First off, a huge shout out to Cornelius Fichtner. PM Prepcast is a genius staff to crack PMP.

I have seen lot of reviews saying that PM Prepcast questions are the most close to actual exam. Well, I am not going to comment on that but what I can say that solving PM Prepcast questions and reviewing all the answers (both correct and incorrect ones) gave me real confidence to take the real exam.

It was only after taking PM Prepcast exams I felt like I was ready for the real exam. I have scored consistently between 82% to 86% in all the seven full length Prepcast exams and more than 90% in few timed quizzes.

I have passed the PMP exam few weeks ago with 4AT 1T and I am really proud of my achievement.

Finally, my advise to all the PMP aspirants would be that most of the questions, if not 100%, are situational. Hence, understanding the underlying concepts of PMBOK guide and getting clarity of thoughts are key to pass the exam. The time required to achieve that may vary person to person. Hence, planning (in terms of time required for studying the concepts, completing few mock tests and finally scheduling the exam) is very important as the case with exam questions too.

Following three things are very important
1. Over preparation
2. Under preparation
3. Unwanted time gap between the time when you feel you are ready to take the exam and the date of real exam.

I am willing to help PMP aspirants with my limited knowledge (iamniladri@gmail.com).

Happy learning!< /review>< pics>

<Text>This course along with the PMP Simulator lead to me passing my PMP exam with "Above Target" in all 3 areas. I didn't purchase the RITA nor did I purchase the Agile book published by PMI. It was literally the normal PMBOK, the course, and the Exam simulator that got me through. The simulator really prepared me for the real exam.

I took away a star because I purchased the course before the exam switched and there wasn't enough "required" (it is available as supplemental, and optional) course material on hybrid/agile projects which is a must have (though if you purchase the exam simulator you will have access to plenty of practice questions on this).

I also took away a star because some of the new exam simulator questions were a little less complex in the sense that I had to answer almost a flashcard type of answer, rather than show that I understood the concept . For frame of reference, I had access to the Exam simulator for the old version of the PMP Exam, and noticed that there were a lot more concept questions, leading me to expect that as the content creators get more accustomed to the new format, the questions will become a bit more complex.

Overall, I can't complain though, because I did also pass with flying colors :). I would highly recommend this product to any and all who are interested in taking the PMP exam.<//Text>< UserId.>

<Rate>5</Rate><text>I am now a proud PMP! Gave the 2021 exam and passed on the first attempt Above Target (2) and Target (1).

PM prepcast is an absolute MUST. I never got the chance to do the simulation exams but I was able to attempt 50-100 quiz questions for each knowledge area. The explanations against every choice provided are super and really help clear a lot of concepts and gaps in your knowledge.

In the actual exam, one doesn't have the time to think much - the answers should come to you instinctively and that happens when you have practiced enough.

There is absolutely no need to memorize the process chart and there is certainly no need to memorize the ITTOs. Just understand and think like a PM. < Review>
Worth every penny! I'm glad I found this course.
It assisted me every step of the way to get PMP certificate; from how to apply for the exam to what to do on the exam date. And I passed the exam on the first attempt =).

I purchased PM PrepCast premium which included exam simulator. I had two months to study because it was already Oct 2020, and I didn't want to deal with the new 2021 exam. The course was so flexible and I could adjust it to fit my own schedule. I skimmed through all VDOs once before actually applied for the exam because I wanted to fill out project management experiences section with PMI terminology and concept following PMBOK guide; was hoping that it could help me avoid application audit. I was told that the audit was random, but still I just wanted to avoid it everyway I could. After my exam application was confirmed, I went through all VDOs again together with PMBOK guide, took notes, memorized process group and knowledge area mapping, and then hit the simulator. Since I didn't have much time I only did 4-hr exam simulator twice, and several 20-question quizzes.

I think both the course and simulator are really useful, especially if you have a tight preparation period. The course helped me to understand underlying concept of PMBOK guide in a short time, and the simulator helped me to get the sense of how the question would be asked in the exam and also time management. Thank you Cornelius and team for such a helpful product.< /Review>

{'time': 1600715097033, 'text': 'Congratulations on passing your exam on your first try! Thank you for taking the time to leave a good review and provide helpful feedback.'}</Resp>
<pics>None</pics>< Review>
The PrepCast provides video lessons which are quite useful. I used them in conjunction with the exam simulator (which has to be bought separately, but is a must-buy), and passed the PMP exam on my first attempt. I can honestly say that while the PrepCast exam simulator stressed me out with its initial results, it prepared me well for the PMP exam. I had not taken such a long and tricky exam - well, ever. The actual exam ended up being simpler than the simulator for me.
PrepCast features:
- Videos are well presented, with lots of examples and tie-ins to the PMBOK guide for ease of following along
- There is an exhaustive table of contents, making it easy to focus on specific content areas of the PMBOK if that's what you need
- There are plans to help you manage your time so you can go at your own pace but optimize your project: Succeeding at the PMP exam
- The exam simulator provides plenty of options for taking full-length or shorter exams, going through answers, and checking areas where you are strong/weak for follow-up study (again, I highly recommend this, it was instrumental in my success)

All-in-all, a great tool for self-study at a fraction of the cost of most PMP preparation programs out there. I highly recommend it!</Review>

{'time': 1614978339032, 'text': 'Congratulations on passing your exam on the first try! Thank you for sharing a wonderful review of our PM Exam Simulator.'}< /resp>
<pics>None</pics><Text>The PrepCast worked for me greatly, suggested to me by a friend who passed his PMP exam in first attempt. I only had a limited time to study this and attempt. Initially, I booked exam for 22nd on 10th of Dec but after attempting the 10 questions' small tests on PrepCast, my confidence level increased and I realized that I can pass my test in first attempt so pushed my exam date another 8 days. And YES, I did pass on the very first attempt. The questions in actual PMP exam were worded a bit different than PrepCast (for certain), but attempting 4 full tests on PrepCast gave me the whole idea of what am I up against.

Studying is definitely a must. I had access to Barbra Walter's videos from my job, which helped me make notes in ZIM Wiki to summarize my brain dumps for revisions. Multiple attempts on all the topics increased visibility on topics and it was amazing.

What can be improved in PrepCast is, giving choice of mixing the topics together for random tests rather than selecting one topic only. Because when you are attempting the one topic, you already know some of the answers. But when you are mixing the topics together then you get to pay a bit more attention.

One thing which is important is that in real PMP exam, the review screen came right after 90 question and I had no choice other than reviewing and then proceeding to rest of 110 questions. Whereas PrepCast simulator offers review of all questions at the end... So when using PrepCast, do it yourself so that you've a better idea of time management.< /Text>< time>

I would highly recommend PMPrepCast!  I just passed the PMP 2021 Exam yesterday with 3/3 Above Targets and this company was instrumental in that process.

<username>Nitin Garg</username><Gmap_id>0x80dcdaea30496c3b:0x6197bf09e1400df8< /Gmap_id><Date>1612297398426< /Date><Review>I took PMP simulator from Prepcast in Nov 2020 for my exam that was scheduled in Dec 2020. It was a tough decision to select which venor to  chose as there are so many simulators available in market. After reading offerings from multiple vendors, i finally decided to chose Prepcast for 2 reasons:
1. They offered 8 sample papers
2. I was not sure if i will be able to clear my exam in Dec and was worried that a new PMP format will be released in Jan so i will have to buy a new simulator. PM prepcast was offering new version simulator free of cost with subscription. So i decided to go with Prepcast.

I was least confident in my preparation when i started taking tests. So, i read through their instructions on how to start using simulator.
Here is my experience:
1. I started with 20 questions to know how does simulator work
2. Then i took 50 questions random knowledge area test.
3. Then i reviewed all my responses and explanations. This was the best part as i could relate my logic to actual logic.
4. Response time of Prepcast customer service team is really very fast. I had few doubts and they immediately replied.
5. Then i started giving full 4 hour tests with 1 day of exam and 2nd day for review.
6. I cleared my PMP exam in first shot. Thanks to Prepcast.
7. 1 important point: The exam instructions and pre exam pointers and how to prepare for day of exam was very helpful. It helped to ease my nervousness.

Few improvement areas:
1. Actual exam gives 10 min break after 89th question. Prepcast should also add this feature. It is very difficult to sit for 4 hours without break as every minute is crucial while attempting exam
2. 3 months of validity period is too short. The time period should be extended.

Overall, i am happy and satisfied with my decision of chosing Prepcast. Thank you team.< /Review><Rating>4<//Rating></record></dataset><record>

<Date>1598266452654</Date>< Review>
The PMP simulator package is well worth the money and a good investment to increase your chances to pass the PMP exam. The practice exams and quizzes are set up well. Take sufficient time to go through the answers and to read all the background explanation, this was very valuable and an important component in my preparation for the PMP exam. I have answered a total of 1305 out of the total 1610 questions in the PMP simulator and completed 6 out of the 8 exams.
I have passed the PMP exam in my 1st attempt, with above target for all 5 process groups.
I would like to give some recommendations for further development of the PMP simulator: The PMP simulator questions generally contain more context compared to the questions in the actual PMP exam. My suggestion is to include more ambiguous questions, only containing 1 sentence without much context, in the simulator. This was the most noticable difference comparing the simulator to the real exam.<//Review>

<Review>The PM Prepcast was the key resource for my passing the PMP with 3 ATs. After failing the test, I then learned of PM Prepcast through a Reddit form. I signed up for the PM Prepcast Premium package, studied and passed with a very solid performance.
There are elements that make the PM Prepcast a great study tool.
1. There are clear objectives for each topic. The length of each module is a perfect length for adult learning.
2. The modules are available as podcasts. I could listen while I went on my daily walk.
3. The test taking advice was very valuable. I took four full 200 question practice exams before I sat for the official PMP test. The content was very true to the format of the actual exam. I was mentally and physically ready for the exam.
4. Cornelius's tone and enthusiasm got me through all the processes.

I will be sure to purchase more learning from Cornelius Fichtner/OSP International  for continuing education and other PMI exam preparation.< /Review><user>112373755094292400827</user></record></dataset><record>
< Review>
The PM exam simulator is an excellent platform to prepare you for the PMP exam.  I passed the exam on my first attempt and this was due in great part to this simulator. The simulator is not just a question bank but a reserve of explanations that clarify any doubts you may have of questions. Their  customer support is also very responsive and will clarify for you almost immediately any conflicts of perceptions you may have with questions on the platform.

For my exam preparation outside of the 36 hours of mandatory taught sessions I committed to steady preparations for roughly 2 months before the exam. During this period I dedicated every Sunday morning at 2 am to sit a mock exam for the full 4 hrs. Intermittently throughout the week i would then do 1 hr stints of 50 questions. The review of the questions you got wrong is what is ABSOLUTELY ESSENTIAL. This is where you get to really grasp the concepts and learn based on the responses and the explanations given. Doing this along with reading and listening to the RITA MULCHAY PMP Exam Prep book really prepared me for this exam.

It was a challenging experience coupled with work but was made bearable with these resources. All the best if you decide to take the plunge, it will be a rewarding experience.< /Review>

<text>I highly recommend using the PM PrepCast for the PMP exam.

My experience:
I worked through all of the PrepCast training course videos over a few months and took notes through each video. These videos are very detailed and this took a long time. After having a decent understanding of the concepts, I took the seven practice exams over about a month. I only referenced the PMBOK Guide when reviewing the practice exams. I then took the exam and passed. From start to finish, it took about 6 months while working fulltime. Felt like I actually over studied for the exam.

If I were to do it again:
I believe the PrepCast training videos are a great resource but the detail they go into is more valuable for overall PMP knowledge rather than for just passing the exam. I would have most likely just watched the videos and skipped taking notes. The real value from PM PrepCast are the practice exams. By working through them, reviewing incorrect answers, and then using the training videos or the PMBOK guide to review gaps, I think I could have passed the exam in 2 months. I also recommend Ricardo Vargas' video on the PMBOK Processes which layouts the overall flow of the PMBOK process/ knowledge areas.

Overall I believe the PrepCast training platform is a good value and can be used by itself to pass the exam.<//text><GmapID>0x80dcdaea30496c3b:0x6197bf09e1400df8< /GmapID>< username>

109014962164426785494< /user>
< review>
Hi everybody,
First I purchased the small package with the videos. It was great to listen, but it is a lot of hours/material. I am not a native speaker and just the listening helped me a lot. As busy as we are all, if you work full time, I got lousy and did not spend soo much time as I should. Then I took advantage of the 4x 6am to 8am  class in August. The good thing about the class was, that you are morally forced to  listen to all the units to keep up. Could I have mastered the exam yet? No!
Fact is unfortunately, you have to dig in unit by unit and there is not really a lot of written material, so I made it myself, more just videos AND several 200 question exams!
This is, how I made it work: I printed 49 pages  with the title of each process and the definitions.  Every Sat. I took a 4h-exam and during the week, I reviewed  my mistakes and made notes in the different process sheets.
In addition, I developed also "documents" like the Project Charter, Project Management Plan, Scope Management Plan etc. and added information.
At the end, you have to learn it in your own way, paste and how you understand and memorize everything.=
Last Tuesday I passed on the first attempt.
Good Luck,
Judith Hage, PMP<//review>

FROM FAIL TO PASS IN 10 DAYS!

Good Day All.

My success story was crowned toady Wednesday 24th December 2020,around 2am (WAT).

I wrote the PMP exam on Monday 14th December 2020, but failed it, even though I was Above Target in three (3) areas.

I was discouraged but decided to reschedule it for Wednesday 23rd December 2020, just 9 days after I wrote it.

I knew I had to do a crash course and needed simulation exams, so I searched on Google and the success stories I saw, convinced me of PM PrepCast PMP simulation exams.

I purchased the PMP simulation exams on Wednesday 16th December 2020 and with a spirit of revenge, aggressively did as many tests and reviews as I could.

The explanations of the PrepCast Exam answers were top notch and I was able to discover and fill gaps in my knowledge.

Even though I did only 6 out of the 8 tests in the simulation, as the time to retake was very short, the exam simulations helped me turn my Fail to Pass, after 10 days.

I initially thought it impossible, but the simulation exams built my knowledge and confidence, to retake and pass the exam.

PM PrepCast is a must have for anyone who desires to pass the PMP.

Will surely recommend to anyone who intends to take the PMP exam.

I am grateful to the PM PrepCast Team.<//review>

<Rate>5< /Rate><text>At the end of the day the PM-Prepcast was awesome, and it definitely helped me pass the exam. Not only were the podcasts great and convenient, but the practice/simulation questions were very similar to those on the actual exam. Thanks PM-Prepcast! And Godspeed to all preparing for their certification!
My process - Purchased PM PrepCast Elite on 8/19. Built a plan to listen to all of the podcasts over the course of a few weeks. Took notes in Excel as I was listening, and would pause if I needed to really comprehend what I was hearing/seeing. I'd do multiple videos per day, typically 2.5 hours or so at 1x speed...but a great personal hack of mine is to listen to podcasts at 2x to get through them quicker. As an experienced PM going into my certification studies, I already 'knew' a ton of the material. Because of this, also, I didn't think it was necessary to purchase the PMBOK Guide. Upon registering to apply for the exam, I went ahead and purchased membership to the PMI, which includes the 6th Edition of the PMBOK Guide, and net it was a little cheaper than just paying for the exam. Upon completion of the podcast plan, I went through each knowledge area of the PMBOK Guide and highlighted key points that seemed like great exam material. I went back through this the week leading up to the exam, honing in on the areas that I highlighted. I also took a number of timed quizzes to get a feel for the material and the timed nature. I'm very happy I did. The longest I did was 100 questions (i.e., half of the actual exam). The actual exam that I passed on 12/14 was LONG.<//text><username>Mitch Curry</username><date>1608498726463< /date>< user>

I just passed the PMP on my first try and I attribute my success to utilizing the PrepCast simulator. I answered over 1400 unique questions, took 9 full practice exams and 30+ quizzes. I loved how the simulator tracked my scores for each test/quiz. This allowed me to focus on specific knowledge and processes where I needed additional studies. Since each answer references the PMBOK, I would go back to it to read that section for more detail.

The PrepCast customer service was excellent! Quick responses to any questions I had about the program. There are also some "freebies" available on the PrepCast website.

I am going to pursue the PMI-ACP and will be utilizing their programs to gain PDUs and access to test simulator.

I HIGHLY recommend this company for anyone wanting to feel confident about taking the PMP test. The actual exam was very similar to the PrepCast practice tests and I felt prepared!

<gmap_id>0x80dcdaea30496c3b:0x6197bf09e1400df8</gmap_id>< Text>
I got Above Target in all 5 process groups. Here is my take on Prepcast.

Prepcast is a great tool to pass your PMP. It has scenario based questions to get us ready for real exam. I recommend to use Prepcast exam simulator in the following way to get best results after attending instructor lead training for PDUs.

1. First read PMBOK once. Do not spend more than 2 hours for each chapter (3+ 10 process groups).
2. Attempt 2 full tests and review each question (each review takes 6-8 hours as you need to understand why your is answer is right/wrong and other choices are right/wrong.
3. Read PMBOK again. This time, you will get to know what to read precisely from the review exercise. Highlight important points on PMBOK. You may spend 1-1.5 hours on each chapter this time.
4. Attempt 3 more tests. This time, review only incorrect questions.
5. Skim through PMBOK. This time hardly 30 minutes for chapter. Attempt last 3 tests. You will see improvement in your percentage.
6. Use right click option to strike and eliminate the wrong options. This is very important. When you look at answers, you can eliminate 2 easily. Strike them off. After selecting what you think is correct, do not strike the closest answer option. When reviewing incorrect answers after exam, read the reason why the closest answer is right. If the correct answer is not the one you chose or the closest answer option that you didn't strike, it means you either have been doomed or got that concept completely wrong into your mind. Revisit this concept on PMBOK.
7. ITTO test (8) is not much useful for real exam. Don't worry if you got even 50% in that test. More than 80% are scenarios based and 18-19% are direct answers. You may get 3-4 questions related to ITTO.
8. if you score around 75%, you will feel that the real test is far more easier than these practice tests. I felt it.

Use this simulator effectively and streamline your thoughts from concepts to correct answers to the questions.

All the best for your PMP examination.< /Text>

<username>Caitlin Grossman< /username><time>1605987165616<//time>< rate>
5</rate>
<Text>Cornelius Fitchner is a household name among PMP aspirants in online communities like reddit. His Prepcast Exam Simulator was instrumental in my preparation for the PMP exam. I passed my exam last week with 4ATs and 1T. Although I used other study guides, on the basis of my experience with the Exam Simulator alone, I would highly recommend Prepcast products to all PMP aspirants.

The Exam Simulator offers full exams or shorter quizzes in a learning mode and timed mode. I believe there are 1600 possible questions and you can chose whether or not you want your tests to draw upon previously answered questions. When taking a quiz, you have the option to select how many questions you‚Äôd like and from what process group.

Learning mode is not timed, offers hints, and you can review your answer as soon as you‚Äôve answered the question.

Timed mode simulates the actual exam.

In both instances, the correct answer is thoroughly explained, and each incorrect answer includes a brief description of why it is wrong and/or not the best answer. This point is particular important because you will face many difficult situational questions on the exam where they are two plausible answers but only one it the best. Each correct answer is linked to a specific page in the PMBOK.

Once you complete your exam or quiz, you revived a pass or fail mark which also indicates your % correct and an analysis of how you performed in each KA and PG. This is what I used to guide my studies.

You can also compare your scores to other users which serves as another indicator of your exam readiness.

While there is no guarantee that good marks on the simulator will mean that you pass the actual exam, people report that when they are in the 75%+ range with the simulator, you are ready for the actual exam.

Best of luck to you!!</Text>< Pictures>

< Text>
I highly recommend PMP Prepcast. I used it predominantly for the exam simulator module which did a phenomenal job in preparing me for the exam. The format that they use is well done because of how similar the questions are to the real ones, and how detailed the explanations are for why the correct answer is correct and why the other choices are incorrect. There are other (more expensive) prep tools that offer the same module but the questions are not the same quality. Instead of a scenario based question, it will be defining inputs/outputs/tools & techniques. These types of questions are ok but do not prep you for the type of questions that will be on the real exam.

I would strongly advise PMP aspirants to use this simulator module as the basis of your prep. It teaches you the concepts while simultaneously giving you exposure to what exam day will be like. Thank you PMP Prepcast.</Text>

<date>1602543120546< /date><rate>5</rate>< Text>
The PMP Exam Simulator was, without question, the resource that made the difference between passing and not passing the PMP exam.  It provides 1400 questions (1600 if you count the ITTO questions), but the answers are the key component; in learning mode, you can see the correct answer, why it's correct, how they arrived at that answer, and an explanation of each remaining choice for why they're incorrect or not as good.  If you use this as a learning tool rather than purely as an assessment tool, you will almost certainly be able to pass the PMP.  I recently passed the exam with Above Target in every section and would not hesitate to recommend this program to other candidates.<//Text>

I purchased PM Prepcast to get an idea of the exam questions. After clearing the PMP exam with "Above Target" in all domains and in first attempt, I can definitely recommend this to PMP aspirants. The questions are quite similar to the real exam questions i.e. situation based. The detailed description for the wrong questions also help in understanding the misconceptions and/or any gaps in understanding. The simulator allows small quizzes (10-100 questions) that you can take according to the free time you have, and 8 full length Mock exams that simulate the exam environment i.e. time. Highly recommended!< /Review>

<user>114421358316029081039</user><resp>{'time': 1592323271448, 'text': 'Thank you for taking the time to leave a great review. Congratulations on passing your exam!'}<//resp><Rating>5<//Rating><gmap_id>0x80dcdaea30496c3b:0x6197bf09e1400df8< /gmap_id>< text>
I practiced the PM PrepCast simulator questions for my PMP exam and was able to pass with Target and Above Target. Retaking the quizzes over and over again enabled me to learn how to read the questions properly and decipher what information is relevant to the question. You'll also learn to point out key words that are important as well. The length and wording of the questions are similar to the exam which helped tremendously. Once you're done with the quizzes/exams, each question and answer will have explanations to help your understanding.

The only thing that I found different on the exam is that the simulator has options that are a little obvious as to what is right and wrong. The exam usually has two obvious wrong answers and 2 possible right answers.

Overall, I'm very happy I purchased the simulator and practiced the questions to prepare me for the PMP exam.< /text>

<text>I started studying the Rita's book in January, with a goal to finish it in the middle of February, which I did. I took notes and did well in all the tests. I was going to follow that up with a company sponsored boot-camp, but my new colleague swore by the PrepCast as a major reason why she passed her PMP test. I decided to save my company a couple of thousand dollars by opting for the PrepCast instead.

I scheduled my exam for March, but that was cancelled due to COVID-19 pandemic. I was able to reschedule it as an online proctored exam in April and passed it with an overall "above target" grade.

The PrepCast was definitely the best thing I could have bought and used to supplement my studying. The key, for me, was paying close attention to the questions I got wrong and reading the explanations to really understand why the right answers were indeed the correct answers. If you do that and pass the practice tests, you should have no problem passing the PMI exam. ...Thank you, PrepCast team.

<Name>Mark Daniels<//Name><date>1595708915791< /date>< rating>
5< /rating>
<text>I passed my first effort.  The materials available are excellent.  The two items I purchased were PrepCast and the Exam Simulator.
PrepCast
When listening to PrepCast you must pay attention.  Don't watch TV at the same time.  I often listened while taking my morning walk.  Often I would follow in PMBOK.
Exam Simulator
After going throught PrepCast,  the Exam Simulator was used first to take untimed quizzes.  I took a few dozen 30 question, untimed tests and often took tests including only those questions that were incorrect. (600 database plus questions).  My initial scores correct ranged from just over 50% to 62% so don't be discouraged.   I used the "snipping tool" to print all errors AND those questions that were correct but not clearly fixed in my mind.   I probably printed over 1000 pages. When I got my percent up a little and had reviewed all incorrect questions...ONLY THEN did I take Exams 1-3.  Same process here, took the exams untimed first, reviewed incorrect questions and correct questions I was not completely clear on.  I kept stacks of paper roughly sorted from unlearned to unsure.  I got my correct % up to around 85-90%.  Then did my final reviewing before the test - mostly with the printed paper of those questions I was unsure of.  during that final week I went back to review questions I answered incorrectly along with the paper.  My final review was for about a week 4 hours per day including Sat and Sun pretty much for 7 days.

Of course the questions are not the same as on the actual test but the more effort you put in...the better you will do.  Good luck to all.< /text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< resp>

<Review>Think 5 stars are not enough for how great this simulator is. I was very disciplined in my studies. My kids who are so sweet knew mom is studying for PMP.

I have not touched PMBOK even once. I went thru the videos and the simulator. Completed 1600 questions. Loved the way it makes your brain think the answers. Reading the answers was a key to success. I did not take 200 questions, infact I mastered the Knowledge Area. So completed as many questions on simulator per KA.

PMP real life questions were way easier than the simulator. So if you have mastered this simulator, probably you are ready to take the test next day.
I completed the exam in 2 hours 45 mins. It was a breeze. Loved seeing the congratulations note.

** If you are taking exam from home, the pearsonvue does hang. So have patience when that happens during the exam and work with the proctor to resolve issues.

The trick that worked for me is I put in all Processes in the excel and noted the output. (Not the tools and techniques) . This brings a flow to your studies. Once I was clear with outputs, I studied Tools and Techniques. And No, you dont need to remember everything.

Many thanks to Cornelius and team for contributing to PMP learning. Now I am heading for PMI ACP and PREPCAST is the obvious choice.< /Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><response>{'time': 1595277162927, 'text': 'Congratulations on passing your exam! < text>
I have experienced only the exam simulator, but I strongly recommend this as part of your study plan. The questions are written in the same style as and the user interface offers a good simulation to the real exam. Why I chose PrepCast over other similar offers was due to the detailed explanations of the answers, not just the correct one, but each and every wrong one. More importantly, it provided exact references to the source material for the question. This allows you to quickly review the material and understand where you went wrong. One other feature which I used on a couple occasions was asking for feedback on exam questions. I received responses back within 24 hours to clarify my questions so I could better understand the correct answer. I compared against a few other exam simulators and they did not have these benefits. PrepCast also offers a limited money back guarantee and a free test, so there's minimal barrier to entry. I passed my exam on my first try with Above Target, and I was not sponsored or incentivized for my review.</text>

<Rate>5< /Rate><text>I have recently passed the PMP exam and the PM PrepCast - together with the Exam Simulator - has been my best friend throughout this journey. I loved the training lessons and the way the videos and the whole suite were organized. Concepts were clearly explained, I could easily follow along on the PMBOK Guide, and I appreciate that some topics that are not part of the PMBOK Guide while being included in the exam contents outline were discussed and fully explained in the video lessons.
For my preparation I watched all the lessons, including the optional ones, as I found them useful too, to gain further insight on specific topics.

I have tried other courses in the past, before finding the PM PrepCast, and comparing the two experiences I definitely recommend the latter: I liked the fact that it elaborates on the main concepts and provides justification, helping you deeply understanding the processes and their relationships - as opposed to just reproducing the very same concepts presented in the PMBOK Guide, with no relevant insights, basically summarizing each chapter of the PMBOK. At least this was my experience and I found the PM PrepCast fully matching my studying and learning approach.
An added value for me was the possibility to watch them as podcasts, so that I could take advantage of my time commuting every day to study for the PMP exam.
Also, I appreciated it is truly up to date and aligned to the 6th edition of the PMBOK Guide - I would not give it for granted!

The PM PrepCast Exam Simulator was also a pillar in my preparation! I find the wording and the way the scenarios are described very close to those you would find in the real exam. You have 7 full exams, plus one entirely dedicated to ITTOs - which I found extremely useful to improve my knowledge and understanding on this often struggling topic. If you have 4 full hours available, I would recommend to take one of the exams, just to get used to the way you would approach the real exam. But the timed quizzes mode is also helpful, because it helps you practice for the exam based on the time available. Extremely useful are the explanations provided, which truly helped me understand not only the reason why the right answer was the right answer, but also why the other options were wrong.</text>< Pics>

<text>Update: Purchased the PMI-ACP, and just passed that exam today. Anyone looking to pass the PMP or ACP exams should absolutely purchase with confidence.

I just passed the PMP after not passing the first time. These questions are good, but the true value is not the questions it is the detailed answers for both why the answer is right and why all the other answers are wrong. This helped me realize the way the questions would be broken down when I went to sit for the exam today. <userid>100275568013002276413</userid><Name>nikhil kulkarni</Name>< Time>
1585634798291<//Time>
<rating>5</rating>< text>
PASSED MY PMP in 2nd attempt. The review is bit longer, but I'm sure it'll definitely add value.
1st attempt:
Did my first attempt in last year in the month of May. While preparing for the exam, I came across too many study materials such as Kim heldman, Andy Crow, Rita Mulchay, some online material, PMBOK and study material from my local PMI chapter, etc.. After checking for almost a month, decided to follow Rita, Local chapter study material and PMBOK.
Mistakes that I did:
1. Scheduled the exam even before I started the preparation. Became too optimistic about my studies, hence not even rescheduled it.
2. Wasted time in selecting the right study material.
3. Took the online free simulator just a day before my exam. (Not PM Prepcast)
4. Studied very hard and not smart.
5. Didn't practiced for numerical at all. (what a fool I was)

Result was clear, I failed miserably. Couldn't able to understand the questions in the exam, answering them was a way too far. Took almost 4-5 months to recover from this frustration, as I had never tasted the failure before.

2nd attempt:
I wasn't sure if I'll be attempting again for the exam. But PMI kept reminding me about my remaining two attempts, in one of the mails they even reminded me that now I've left with only 3months to take the 2nd attempt otherwise I'll have to reapply, as my one year application validity was getting expired in 3 months. So, one fine day, I took the deep breath, closed my eyes and convince myself to apply for 2nd attempt. This time I was assigned for a project which allowed me very less time for any of my personal works. So, somehow I could manage to get only 1hr in the morning and 1 hr in the evening. Followed below steps to make things right this time-
1. Written down the lessons learned from my previous exam experience.
2. Took the PMPrepcast lessons package, and watched the lessons avg 2hrs per day. (Kept my choice clear)
3. After watching the prepcast lessons, reviewed the local chapter study material and checked PMBOK only for glossary. (only reviewed in brief and not in detail)
4. Though all lessons from prepcast were not completed, I stopped checking any of the material and started with the exam simulator almost 10 days prior to exam.
5. Since I could get almost 2hrs a day, I was unable to take full exams. So, I started with time & learning quizzes. Did all types of quizzes from 10 questions to 100 questions. The results were ranging from 53% to 90%. Took only one full exam and scored 80%.
6. AND THAT WAS THE BANG!!! The learning from these questions were amazing. I could able to understand the thought process behind every question that is being asked.
7. I checked the explanation of all the wrong questions and then could able to relate what is being asked. This helped me gain confidence. I was so happy that at least now I was able to understand the questions and could able to figure out the best possible answer.
8. Prepared for all the possible numerical and memorized the necessary formulas. Solved avg 5 numerical per formula. (What an easy task it was!)
9. After taking almost 500 questions from the simulator, now I was confident enough that I can pass the exam with at least T's in all areas.

And this worked, the actual exam questions seemed very easy and I finished my exam with almost 20min left. And not even T but secured AT in all areas.
Thanks to PM Prepcast.
Last word. EXAM SIMULATOR IS A MUST. DON'T MISS IT AT ANY COST.</text>

When I finally passed the PMP, I had two weeks left on my application, so it was do or die time,  I discovered that after studying all the process groups, all the knowledge areas, and going through the PMBOK - testing, and getting into "test-taking mode" is absolutely key to passing the PMP Exam. <Text>I searched for self-paced training to earn the required PDU's for the PMP certification.  I found Cornelius Fichtner and the PrepCast.  It looked like it had good reviews and the price was actually lower than I was anticipating.  I purchased the course and the exam-prep plus some other training offered in the bundle.

The course was perfect.  I listened in podcast mode on my way to and from work and any time I could and then I wen through the same material but watched it on my computer.  The slides were helpful to learn the concepts more in-depth.  I took notes so I could do a review later of the material I thought would be important.  In total I watched all of the courses atleast once, some topics twice and then I listened in podcast mode to all of them a few times.  (Also read the PMBOK through the course)

I passed the course exam and printed the course certificate and submitted my application to the PMI.  My application was accepted.  Then I get an email from Dan Ryan about a weekend bootcamp sort of training I signed up that and that was a quick review of the course.  This all helped me learn the material.

Then I started getting exam ready by taking all of the tests in Dan's course.  That helped be realize the areas I really needed to review. I took all of Dan's prep tests.  Once I passed those at a good rate.  I went back to the Exam prep that came with the PM PrepCast bundle and those tests were very helpful!  I took 2 full 4 hour exams and did well and then went through the formula course and related exam to make sure I knew that.  After passing 2 4-hour exams and a few 100 and 200 question exams I was ready to sign up for the real exam.

I should have signed up earlier as the available test times were about a 4 weeks away.  I was hoping to take the exam much earlier.  Then luckily I found a spot that was much earlier than I planned... Like 3 days away.  I took a leap of faith and signed up for that date.  (My advice is set a date earlier in your process.)  Anyway, I felt well prepared and did well I the exam.  I passed!</Text>< Name>

< Review>
When I started studying PMP, There were many options to choose from. After researching & reading feedbacks, I decided to go with PrepCast. Initially, I opted for 1-week free simulator & then I went with full access. The good thing about PrepCast is, you have the option to learn with & without time restrictions. Some pro/cons (not actually cons but I can see areas of improvements)
Pro:
1. 1600 questions are a lot.
2. Flexibility to choose from how to do study. Means time based, knowledge area-wise, Process groups wise etc.
3. Every question and/answers are precisely narrated.
4. The difficulty level of English or grammar or sentence structure is somewhat similar to the real exam.
5. Cool thing is, Reference given of PMBOK guide.

Cons (Not actually)
1. The orientation of PrepCast is somewhat not inline with the real exam. like,
a. In the real exam, you will have an in-built calculator (soft calculator).
b. The real exam has no option to highlight and/or straight-out the wrong answers whereas PrepCast has.
c. Real Exam show time in minutes in descending order (240, 239, 238) whereas PrepCast shows in HH: MM format. Whereas in PrepCast it's easy. It difficult in the real exam to correlate the time with questions remaining. So just want to have consistency with the real exam.
2. I found PrepCast somewhat easier than the Real Exam.
3. Keep in mind, there is no feature in the real exam to zoom in/out the page whereas you can do the same in PrepCast Simulator (using Cntl+/-Mouse cursor).

Overall, I am happy with PrepCast for my PMP preparations. This has helped me to prepare & made ready for the real exam. I recommend buying PrepCast & complete at least 6-7 PMP Exam from the simulator.

Not to forget: Tips received in the emails (new sellers) were helpful. It's good to have them for a quick study.

Thank You PrepCast.<//Review>

< text>
In terms of quality, the PM-Prepcast and the associated exam simulator are excellent tools for preparing for the PMP exam.  I do not believe that they are the only tools one should use, however.  You must have the PMBOK Guide as well; and my learning style also required a good workbook to accompany the Prepcast to make the material more real for me.  The exam simulator was exactly on target with the style and types of questions found on the PMP exam.

I used the computer-based LMS system almost exclusively.  I tried the podcast version a number of times  using Andriod-based podcast apps but always found them frustratingly clunky and difficult to manage.  Perhaps it was because of the apps or my unfamiliarity with the interface, but I essentially gave up after some time and resorted back to the desktop/laptop version.

All in all, the PM-PrepCast can be an essential tool for your preparation for the PMP exam.  I strongly recommend it.<//text>

<username>Ashish Patwardhan<//username><Time>1558947906550< /Time><rate>4</rate>< review>
Pm-precast simulator is an excellent simulator package!

The best feature about simulator is - detailed explanation of all the correct and incorrect options explaining why the particular answer is correct and other options are incorrect. This helps you to think ‚ÄòPMI way‚Äô and this comes very handy during actual exam.

Another excellent feature (which I used quite a lot) is ‚ÄòLive Feedback‚Äô where you can post your comments/questions/queries regarding the answered questions and options. You get a detailed reply usually within 24 hours explaining why a correct option is correct and why others are incorrect.

The questions are up to date w.r.t PMBOK6 version. The simulator questions resemble actual exam questions. The user interface is good and user friendly. With strikeout feature you can eliminate the wrong answers and visualize and choose between remaining options.

However I would suggest adding highlight feature (just like actual exam) to highlight important keywords / cues in the question.< /review>

<user_name>Laura Kelly< /user_name><review>I started this journey about a year ago with very little business acumen even though I had been leading projects for years. Yesterday I passed the PMP exam for certification, my second attempt.

I wish I would have invested in PrepCast first. Prior to my first attempt, I started with reading the PMBOK and then I entered into an online course through a local university. It was nothing like PrepCast. It was 99.99% reading on your own with no audio or video...not the way I learn. After that first certification attempt I gave myself a month off. I then turned to PrepCast. I heard a number of people that passed the exam on first attempt when using the program.

At the beginning of each week I committed myself to completing a certain number of videos and or time based on my work/life schedule. I would at times allow myself a day off. I also purchased the test simulator. I completed most of the simulator through the learning format, not timed. Then, once I finished all test questions once, I took exams of only questions I answered incorrectly. Marking the wrong questions to correct answer if answered wrong again-taking advice from others not to review wrong answers multiple times. My test scores on first attempts were around 75%. Test scores were consistent and I had done all that I could studying and reviewing. I was ready. It took approximately a month to complete the videos and a month of test simulate.

Suggestions, in no particular order:

-invest time in support- network,
-the application completion takes a lot of time - before opening application, gather details, prepare your 500 word descriptions of projects and review details/give heads up to your contacts on application,
-brain dump formulas at start of exam even if you think you know it,
-make a firm commitment to study time,
-discuss extreme test anxiety with your doctor and PMI,
-do not memorize ITTOs - understand why such and such is an ITTO,
-understand that what needs to be done next for an iterative process is not necessarily in the flow of the process chart,
-spend time on understanding the change management process,
-there are number of ways that you can graphically see a critical path, free float or total float question, be prepared,
-success in this process will need to be achieved in your own manner, lessons learned are not the Bible,
-treat your preparation, test day and entire process like the project manager you are!< /review>< rate>
5</rate>

<username>gabriel spena< /username>< Pics>
None< /Pics>
< Review>
I have passed the PMP exam on April 10th, with overall Above Target result (4 KA Above Target, 1 KA "Closing" in Below Target). The exam was very mind demanding regarding the time scope, you don¬¥t have enough time to think deeply each answer so you have to chose the option very quickly. There were 4/5 EVM very basic questions, and all of them uses the same sample so you don't have to recalculate all basic values (EV, CV, SV, etc.) again. The was one easy schedule question, and roughly 1/3 questions are straight forward, 1/3 situational but easy ones and another 1/3 that you never will know if you answered well or not!! When doing Prep Cast exam tests, I tried to write down the 10 KA and 44 Process in the very first minutes of the test, but it takes more than 10 minutes and that will be precious time for answer all the questions. Based on my experience, I recommend to avoid this and only memorize the 5 Process Groups, 10 KA and all the process (most of them are repetitive) but don't waste time writing down them. What I think is more important is to write down the formulas, you can do it in a couple of minutes and it is very helpful when you are in a rush and you don't want to waste time remembering every time you need them and are prone to make mistakes after 3 hours of extensive reading and thinking.
Regarding my personal experience with Prep Cast. it was very positive, both with the course and with the test models. The classes cover all the PMBOK, the explanations on the ITTO's are clear and they cover the necessary for the PMP exam. The design of the presentations is very good, and the scope of them perfectly covers what is required in the exam. I recommend it either to those who need a course that can be done at different times or those who prefer to do it at their own pace and from any location. I took 2 month full time (5/6 hours a day) for preparing, my method was to watch PrepCast videos for one KA at a time and then read the same KA in the PMBOK. After I complete the Prep Cast course, I read the PMBOK once again, and then I took 5 test exams, with rating 72, 73, 77, 82 and 86.5.< /Review>

<Rating>5</Rating><UserId.>103158945404796295466<//UserId.>< review>
PM PrepCast was instrumental in passing my PMP. Their practice exams are the closest to the real thing of any test out there. With the knowledge that I was passing their practice tests and quizzes above target, I went into my exam calm and confident and passed above target in 2:30.

Prepcast has the best practice exams for a number of reasons:
1. Their questions are the most similar in language and difficulty to the real test.
2.  They explain the motivation and identify trick words in the questions.
3. They tell you why the right answer was right.
4. They tell you why the wrong answer was wrong.
5. They tell you the reference pages in the PMBOK Guide for further reading.
6. The user interface is the closest to the real test. (i.e. mouse buttons do the same thing etc.)

I'm definitely recommending them as a study tool to my friends/colleagues that are getting their PMP certifications.< /review>

<text>First of all, I failed PMP test on my first try. Yes, first try, despite going through all the necessary protocol: I went through the training for requisite 37 hours, read the PMBOK Guide cover to cover and with the assistance of some Free Simulation Sites for more than three months.
My exam was CBT and at first I was very confident, but immediately I attempted the first 10 questions I got completely demoralized. I immediately realized the exam questions were all scenario-based questions unlike the questions adopted by the Free Simulation Sites I reviewed before the exam. The truth is that the PMP exam evaluates your understanding of the PM concepts not just what you have memorized from the Guide.
As an IT person, I have written over 10 certification exams over the years but that was the first exam I failed, so that experience was a serious disappointment. After the exam, I knew i must change my approach in order to succeed on my second try. First of all, I knew i had to get some additional materials to augment the PMBoK guide and again find a simulation site that has a scenario-based questions to test my preparations. I had a discussion with my immediate boss (who is PMP Certified too) in the office and he was surprised I didn't even read Rita Mulcahy book before sitting for the exam. So I later went to the internet and reviewed the best PMP simulation sites and the result showed the PM Prepcast site has the highest rating among many sites evaluated by Google users. Remember my new approach was getting additional materials and signing for PM Prepcast simulation, because the truth is that the pmp test syllabus covers merely 75% pmbok guide designed in a scenario-based style. I immediately signed for PM Prepcast simulation (only) and read the new materials side by side with the pmp guide for another three months before my second try.
On the 9th of March 2019, I sat for the test (Paper Based Test this time around) again and luckily I received my result on the 27th March and passed with flying colours (four ATs and one T) courtesy to this new approach. I must give credit to Prepcast, because all its questions are tailored in a scenario-based approach, and I can testify like many other pundits, that their questions are more difficult than the real pmp exam.
Based on my personal experience, If I‚Äôm to compare the difficulty level of the two, and let‚Äôs assume the pmp exam is on level 1, then Prepcast simulation must be on level 3. Remember, even in ordinary Game, higher levels are more difficult and I suppose that was the model the developers exploited in deploying the Prepcast questions-bank. As Expected, my exam went smoothly and in fact I got to the ‚ÄòFinish Line‚Äô 20 minutes earlier. I utilized the 20 minutes to review the marked questions and all other questions with calculation.
For me, the PM Prepcast is the best pmp simulator in the world and I will always recommend it to other PMP aspirant. So far I have recommended it to two of my colleagues presently undergoing PMP classes.</text>< user>

<UserId.>105487004004540009962</UserId.>< pictures>
None<//pictures>
< Text>
10 stars for the PM PreCast practice questions/simulator. I had the mock questions for only one month. December 28 - Feb 1st. Took my exam on Feb 2nd and I passed.

My strategy - Studied Rita book twice, and did couple of practice questions and scored 74% on the simulator in late November. I still felt like something was missing. Around mid December I came across PM prepcast via a friend, I went through few questions and right then I knew that this was what I needed. Yes it closely mirrors the real exam. Overall, it's a little bit more sophisticated than the real exam. Which is a good thing.

My analogy is that if you practice with robust and tough questions, the exams will be easier. It's like going into a boxing match with your friend after you have successfully sparred with Mike Tyson. You will knock your buddy out easily. LOL. Yes it worked, thank God!!

Make these practice questions your best buddy, bring them with you everywhere! I take few questions every chance that I get. At home on my laptop, on my smart phone when I'm out. Sometimes when I'm in the parking lot of a grocery store I quickly do 10 questions, review the ones I got right and the ones I got wrong. Read all the explanations to the multiple choices. This is GOLD!! That's how you actually learn.

You acquire 40% knowledge from studying books/materials and the rest 60% is in practice questions. These practice questions conditions your brain/mind to understand how the PMP questions are being structured. Take short questions 10 -30, review and repeat until you are through with the whole question bank. Then go back and revisit the ones you failed. There's a 90% chance that you will pass if you dedicate your time and follow this strategy.

Finally don't waste your time studying the PMBOK. You don't need it to pass the exam!! I read the PMBOK for only 20 minutes and never revisited it. Thank you PM PrepCast and good luck to all the PMP aspirants!!<//Text>
<response>{'time': 1549568239992, 'text': "Thank you so much for giving us TEN STARS! That's very much appreciated!"}< /response>< GmapID>

We appreciate your recommendation.'}< /resp><user_id>116747429036690041936< /user_id><Rate>5< /Rate><Review>I previously used Rita's Course Book and its FastTrack questions and I did not get close to passing the test.  Second time around I spent some time understanding the PM processes using a book by Andy Crowe, which helped me retain some of the processes.  Finally I started testing myself via Prepcast.  Hands down this is the best software to learn the processes and understand what situations to use them in.  The answers to the questions give you a full explanation of why all of the wrong answers are wrong and why the correct answer is the best choice. There are over 1000 questions.  The questions can be broken down between knowledge areas, process areas, answered wrong, unanswered questions, timed, and learning tests.  Furthermore, you can see your all of your test scores over time which helps you see that you have made progress.  I started out at 30%-60% on my first 10 question tests.  By the time I finished using the tool, I was regularly getting between 80%-100% on 10 question tests.  When I saw my progress I knew I was ready for the test.  I took it and the test was so easy for me I got bored 100 questions into it.  I also passed at close to above target, but still in the on target range.  I highly recommend this tool!

< review>
There are many ways to prepare for PMP certification, the most important is always your personal project experience. However, I found that going through PrepCast (after reading PMBOK) was a great way to relate the PMBOK material with real life projects. Exam result: pass
Above target - initiating

Target- execution
Target - monitor controlling
Below target - closing

The most similar questions came from the practice quizzes and exams from PMPREPCAST. Those were very very similar to the real thing.

My exam prep: I took an in-person 10-week class at Oklahoma City University, we met once a week. I also completed an online class after that PMPREPCAST (Cornelius) AFTER I completed the 10-week class.

<Pictures>None<//Pictures><text>The PMP Exam Simulator Premium was one of the critical keys to my success in passing the PMP on my first attempt.  Being able to take shorter, customized quizzes allowed me to focus on weak areas, shore them up, then re-quiz to improve.

My $.02 is to take a baseline full exam, take 10-15 question quizzes in each of the knowledge areas, study what you get wrong, then re-take the focused quizzes until you pass each 3 times.  Then re-take a full exam and see how you do, rinse, and repeat.  The Simulator provides the closest test experience compared to the real PMP.

Godspeed everyone,

<time>1530874635105</time><rating>1</rating><review>During the year of 2017 I was planning to enter the PMP exam but could not even schedule it due to the usual busy schedule at work (the real reason being not assigning the needed priority to this matter). Then at the end of December 2017 I heard the exam contents changes to PMBOK6 in March 2018 but again it was only at the end of January 2018 when I became PMI member and scheduled the exam for March 20, 2018 (the latest free slot that I could find for my location).
I spent the whole February to complete only the thorough reading of PMBOK5, spending on average 2 hours per day (4 hours on weekends) since I continued to go to office. Then in March 2018 I decided to take 2 weeks off to have full dedication for studying Rita's Book supported by free exam simulators and Cornelius Fichtner videos from OSP International, a pocket exam book of Rita, some exam questions from previous trainings (I had attended one formal 36-hour PMP prep course back in December 2014 outside office and an additional one in 2017 at office, both based on PMBOK5) During the last two weeks I studied 8-10 hours per day on average. Besides, I have worked in project and program management in 2014-2017 period. During the preparation for the exam in the moments when I felt I would not make it due to shortage of time to prepare properly for the exam, the two advices that I liked most were 1) Do not over study! 2) Not all of the questions at the exam will be that difficult. I did not run any mock exam with more than 20 questions at a time. Since I heard a lot of warnings that many run out of time during the exam, my strategy at the exam was to quickly pass and answer ALL the questions by marking the ones that I was not sure about. I marked some 25-30 and had couple of questions not answered at all but at the second pass I changed my mind only on two of the marked ones and answered the remaining two. With this much effort and practical work background plus headphones (for full focus) and a single short call-of-the-nature break I was able to pass the exam in my first attempt.< /review><Pics>None<//Pics><Resp>{'time': 1530884634252, 'text': 'Congratulations on passing the exam on such a tight schedule, Erg√ºn. < time>
1520368896968< /time>
<Review>First of all, thank you, Cornelius for your outstanding work on the PrepCast series.  The series was my first set of material used in my PMP exam prep journey. I passed the exam, thanks to the concise yet comprehensive material.  Although it is recommended by most to read the PMBOK guide cover to cover several times, I had skimmed it only once. I tried reading it a second time but found that it took too long.  I resorted to using the copious notes I had taken while listening to your podcasts.  That worked for me.  Along with another study guide,  I was confident enough to pass the exam.

I do have a couple of suggestions:

1 - While I know that the questions in the PMP exam is different for everyone, mine felt like most of the questions had more than one "very good" answer.  It was stressful throughout the exam trying to pick the best one.  My experience with the PrepCast mock exams were a little different in that most of the answer choices were clear that there is only one good answer.  As such, I was able to finish the mock exams within 3 hours every time and score well.  On the real exam, I took the 4 entire hours and could have used a few more minutes to review the marked questions.  The suggestion here would be to incorporate multiple good answers in your questions to better mimic the real exam.

2 - On your calculation questions, it would be good if the bar chart (introduction to the question) is different in every mock exam.  I found that every time I see the same bar chart, I'm "cheating" when I get the question correct because I had seen the chart before and did not need to read the details more carefully.

Thanks once again!</Review>< user_id>

<Review>I used the PrepCast (PMBOK 5th Ed) and a few books to study for my PMP exam, which I passed on the first try. The formula guide that accompanied the PrepCast was very helpful. The lectures, however, contain a lot of repetitive contents (overview of the knowledge area and process groups) and I didn't finished all of the lectures. I took several practice exams using the simulator. The simulator gives a realistic feel of the exam experience. However, some of the practice exam questions on ITTOs are a bit too stringent and I disagree with some of the answers. When I looked up those questions on the 6th Ed of the PMBOK guide, I found that my answers to those questions would be correct based on the updated PMBOK guide, which has more comprehensive and logical ITTOs. Based on my exam experience, the ITTOs asked on the exam can be answered by common sense. The PrepCast discussion forum is excellent. I have found a lot of like-minded students and the discussions are very helpful, as I don't have a local study group. Overall, I think PrepCast is a solid exam preparation product, but I would advise the students to think more broadly on the sample ITTO questions.< /Review><Pics>None< /Pics><Resp>{'time': 1517255542011, 'text': 'Thank you for this comprehensive feedback Angela. We have already addressed two of your critique points: In our new PrepCast Sixth edition we have removed much of the repetition that you have seen. (This also bothered me, so I took action to remove it). And as far as the ITTO questions go, we are reviewing and rewriting every single one of our simulator questions based on the new requirements, style and type of questions on the actual exam. This means that almost all ITTO questions are disappearing. Some will remain but the questions themselves are more situational than knowledge based. In this way new students will not feel the repetitiveness nor have as many ITTO questions.'}<//Resp>< gmapID>
