112075248654908393557< /user_id>
<user_name>Josiah Seale</user_name><time>1505961206833<//time>< rate>
5</rate>
< Review>
Pros:

The PMP certification addresses extremely useful content, but in most cases learning it can be challenging. It's not because the material is complicated, but rather human nature. Let's be honest: learning best practices for putting together e.g. a schedule management plan can make for dry material at best.

Enter Cornelius Fichtner. With an enthusiasm that defies belief, he lays out the material in a thoughtfully logical sequence and pays attention to providing just the right amount of content. It's enough to make the material understandable and retainable without delving too far into the weeds. He explains why the pieces of information he is explaining are important,  and how they connect to the other topics already discussed.

The course is a lot of hours of video (which is also required for it to qualify with PMI) so it requires some determination to get through it, but figuring out I could use ear buds to take my computer to my favorite hookah cafe to sit down with Digital Cornelius was sufficient to (eventually) get me through all of the videos, typically in stints of 2-3 hours at a time.

After completing the PM PrepCast course I comfortably passed the test with highest marks in all sections. Many of the project management experience hours described on my PMI application were with a teensy startup that had run out of money, so I was "randomly selected" for an audit, but it was all verifiably true and PMI was happy with the PM PrepCast as the course I took, so I am now a certified PMP. As a side benefit, after 15-20 hookah cafe stints with Digital Cornelius in 2-3 hour stretches, even a year later I can still pull off a killer Cornelius Fichtner impression to impress all my friends and guests at parties.

A final nice thing about the PM Prepcast is the ability to download the videos -- they are well-organized and succinct, so I put them on a work computer to have them at my fingertips in case I ever need a refresher on some of the finer points. 8/10, would repeat (if I really really had to)

Cons:
For awhile Cornelius's chipper Swiss voice haunted my dreams, happily chattering about earned value management and procurement performance reviews as the soundtrack to a gigantic battle between Godzilla and Biollante, except one of them was actually a Schedule Performance Index and the other was a Cost Performance Index. I got over it though.<//Review>

<Gmap_id>0x80dcdaea30496c3b:0x6197bf09e1400df8<//Gmap_id><review>It took me a lot of time to decide if I want to go for classroom training or online training. Lot of my friends had suggested classroom but I was not comfortable with attending 4 day classes over two weekends. So I decided to go for online training.
Before deciding on pm prepcast I did a lot of research on different online providers. I was looking for good quality videos and good support. After reviewing and reading loads of user comments I finally decided on pm prepcast and it turned out to be a very good decision. Not only the quality of the videos is very good but if you have read Pmbok or any other book (I read Rita) before watching the videos you can very easily relate to the material. The way the content is covered is easy to understand as the video durations are not very long. So you can do one or two in one sitting and not get overwhelmed. I used to do two in mornings and one in evening so it work d out for me.
The other thing I really liked is then way Cornelius has explained how to prepare for the exam and about the application process. It was really very helpful for me as I did not have any other support while preparing. I studied alone and took about 10 weeks to finish the exam. Though I had read pmbok and Rita earlier but it was only after going through the videos that I got confident about the material.
The support is just amazing. I used to post questions and used to get reply very quickly. Thanks for that.
Overall I am very happy that I opted or pm prepcast and cleared the exam in first attempt. Now I have already started to plan for maintaining the certification and I currently reviewing the pdus offered by pm prepcast.
I want to thank Cornelius and whole pm prep cast team.

<time>1506620996632<//time>< Rating>

<Review>I was using the project management prepcast PMP simulator about 2 years ago to prepare for my PMP exam. I tried a few free simulators back then, but liked the prepcast the most. Their simulator has a very nice user interface, and it does not require a download. So you can use it from any place and on any device. Well, I did not test on all of course, but it worked on my Windows laptop and iPhone. Very convenient. The questions in the simulator are comparable with what I eventually encountered on my real PMP exam. But the main feature which I really liked and what I did not see from any other companies, is their live feedback. For example, if you need a clarification on a specific question or you just disagree with the correct answer, you can click the live feedback button right on the screen of that question, and one of their PMP guys gets back to you with a detailed explanation of why the correct answer is really correct. Well, sometimes they were wrong, and I even succeeded to convince them to change some of their questions, which I guess was very helpful for them, but also helped me to gain my confidence in my knowledge. This communication back and forth was highly valuable and helped me a lot. It's like having your own PMP coach for free. Well done, prepcast! I would definitely recommend this product to anyone who is preparing for their PMP exam. Well worth the money and really prepares you for THE day!<//Review><pics>None</pics>< response>
None</response>
